{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fiji_ver02/data/sn83030214/00175039272/1907120101/0004.xml":{"full_text":"CONGRESS TO GO SLOW.\nCONGRESS TO GO SLOW.\nCANNON 4 TRUE PROPHET.\nCANNON A TRUE PROPHET.\nAside from Appropriations, Only\nFinancial Law Likely.\n[From The Tribune Bureau.l}\nwashington, Nov. 30.\u2014Any one who may have\ndoubted the accuracy of Speaker Cannon\u2019s pre\nai~tion. made several months ago, that the first\n<rs<ion of the 60th Congress would pass little\njegisiation other than the regular appropriation\nbilis, would have little ground left for doubt had\n+hev talked with the leaders of the two houses\nof Congress during the last few days. Some\nmeasure of financial legislation, to be passed\nnot immediately but before adjournment, is ex\npected, and practically nothing else.\nThere is notable unanimity of opinion among\nshe influential Republicans concerning the tariff,\nthe view being entertained by all but az few\ndeep-dved standpatters that tariff revision will\ncome immediately after the next President is\ninaugurated. It is a safe assertion that every\nSenate leager, with the possible exception of\nMr. Hale, and fully two-thirds of the Republican\nmembership of the Senate expect a special ses\nsion immediately after March 4, 1808, at which\nthe tariff schedules will be reviewed and nec\nessary changes made.\nThere is some talk in the House of again pass\ning the Philippine tariff bill, providing for free\ngdmission of 2il Philippine products except\ngugar, tobacco and rice, and for collecting on\nthem oniy 00 per cent of the Dingley tariff; but\nno expectation of the favorable consideration of\nsuch a measure is entertained in the Senate,\nand the failure of the President to urge such\njegisiation may go far to prevent its passage by\nthe House.\nIt is expected that before long the Military\nAffairs Committee of the Senate will make a re\nport on its investigation of the Brownsvilie af\nfrey and that Senators Foraker, Bulkeley and\nScott will sign a minority report declaring that\nthey do not consider the guilt of the negro soi\ndlers established, while the remaining members\nof the committee, including five Republicans and\nfour Democrats, will subscribe 10 a report de\nclaring that the evidence clearly establishes the\nfact that the shooting was done by th\u00e9 negro\nsoldiers, but that the committees has found it\nquite impossible to fix the gulit any indi\nviduais. There is a chance that Senator Hemen\nwav may vote with Senator Foraker, in which\n~zse the Republicans would be evenly divided,\nalthough Mr. Hemenway has informally ex\npressed hiz convictior that the negroes did tu\u00bb\nshooting. However, there is no likelihood that\nthe Senate will take any action on the report,\nand it wili probably be filed away in the ar\nchives of the Senzte among a host of other rec\nards of political experiments which came to\nnothing\nOpinion regarding the amendment of the\nfherman anti-trust ect in sccordance with the\nrecommendation of the President, is preity even\nIv divided, perhaps a sight preponderance being\nin faver of some 3uch simple amendment as\nehall insert the word \u201cunreasohabie\u2122 before the\nwords \u201ccombinations in restraint of trade,\u201d so\nthat the amended law would prohibit only such\ncombin~tions as resulted in unreasonable re\nstraint.\nsc has already been indicated in these dis\npetcies, the Speaker has practically turned\ndown the projects for increasing the efficiency\nof the percels post and for establishing a\nposta: savings bank.\nTre prospect of tariff revision in 13509 is al\nread beirz discussed as affording additional\nreas whe \u2018he coming seszicn should be ad\njourned as carly as possible, as it is pointed out\ntha: vex: year's session, including the proposed\nspecin! session. will probably last far into the\nsummer. Gf course, the approach of the Presi\ndential campaign will also operate to procure an\nearly sdjournment\nao\nGOV. FREAR ON HAWAII'S NEEDS.\nSays American Laborers to Replace Orientels\nAre Wanted.\nFrom The Tribune Bureau.\nCn lr fi ceca aaar\u00ae\nWashingica, Nov. 30.\u2014Governor W. F. Frear of\nHewzil called on the President to-day to discuss\nlegislation the administration wishes enacted for the\ngood of the islands. The Gevernor wiil remain In\nWashington about two weeis, and hopes 10 interest\n\u2018he holders of the pursestrings in Congress suffi\nlent! to insurs the passage of severai much need\nad bills.\n\u201cTre gre trying very hard to replace the Oriental\nlaborers in Hawa! with a more desirable class of\nzllens from Eurcps\u201d he said. \u201cWe have succeed: d\nin gerting number of Portuguese and Spaniards,\nwho are proving themselves exceiient citizens and\nvaluzble laborers. If we could get more Americans\nin the islands it would be a great heip toward the\nend desired. If they couid hire them. the planters\nwould prefer American laborers, and the Orientals,\nnot finding work, would leave of their own accord.\nA large number of Japanese women have been im\nported within late years, but the men, of course,\npredominate. We need more money from Congress\nto carry on the business of the government out\nthere to advantage, but up to the present we have\nhed no real cause for complaint on the ground of\nCongressional parsimony.\n\n\u201cThe financial panic has hit Hawaii but not sO\nhard es it struck the states. None of the banks\nstopped paying out real money, but business In gen\neral suffered. We are just now bending our ensr\ngles toward developing our pineapple plantations.\nLarge canneries have been established, and, as the\npineapples are declared by experts to be the best\nraised anywhere In the world, there is a blg future\nahezd for the industry. Rubber plantations have\nalso been mizrted, with every prospect of large re\nturns to the investors.\u201d\nADDITION TO NATIONAL FOREST.\nWeshington, Nov. 80.\u2014Arizona now has 220,00\nmore geres of timber land in the Prescott national\nforest by reason of a proclamation creating two\n268iilons which wae signed by the President to\nday. The tracts will be put under forest service\nadministration and protected from fire, theft and\nwaste. The additions will give the Prescott forest\nin area of 1,063,258 acres. It is estimated that there\nare about 70,000,000 board fest of yellow pine in the\nacditions.\nTRACKS HELD TO BE UNSAFE.\nWeshington, Nov. $0.\u2014The Brotherhood of Ralil\nway Trainmen has fled with the Postmaster Gen\neral a complaint against the Missouri Pacific Rall\nway Company for maintaining tracks alleged to be\nunsefe. In view of the fact that the lives of postal\nemployes may be endangered through the running\nof trains over unsafe roadbeds the Postmaster Gen\nerz] is urged to investigate the charges.\nWorks Rap! an\u00e9 Bafely\u2014Rogulren No Ezxercisin\nPoi le You to What You Like\u2014\nCut This\nWorks Rap'diy an\u00e9 el uires No Exercising\nand ATows You to What You Yike\u2014\nCut This Out.\nFor the benefit of those who wish to reduce\ntheir flesh quickly and safely, we will give the\nreceipt and directions in full for a simple house\nid remedy that can be obtained at trifiing\n<ogt from sny good drug store; 1-2 ounce Mar\nmola, 1-2 ounce Fiuid Extract Cascara Aromatic\nund 31-2 ounces Eyrup Simplex. All three are\n\u201cheap and wholesome, nut you should take care\nto get an unbroken package so that you get\nMarmola and not a substitute. When you get\nbome mix the three together by shaking them\nin\nSpoonful after each meal and at bedtime.\nFollow these directions and you will have the\nfat reducer that money can buy. It will\nitks off the flesh at the rate of at least two\nbounds a week without disarranging the stom\n2ch or causing wrinkles, while, best of all, no\nYorcising or dieting is required to help it out.\n10u can get results and at the same time take\neasy and eat what you like\u2014as much as\nHis a ry whenever you like\nNEW-YORK DAILY TRIBUNE, SUNDAY. DECEMBER 1. 1907.\nEthan igh po db\ngund of common sense, \u00a30 +hat the Speake: Wold\nis talents may be of valus\nlike to place him where h\n10 fhe House. Last year the Speaker made Mr.\nOlcett a member of ihe District Committee, and as\nit usually causes hard feeling to taxe a man {rom\nthe foot of a ccmmittes and make him chairman, it\nis not believed that the member from the 15th Dis\ntrict wili be 80 honored, but the District chairman\nship might be given to Mr. Vreeland and the Ap\npropriations chairmanship to Mr. Olcott, glthough\nthe ranking member, Samuel W. Smith, of Michi\ngan, is the most likely candidate.\n\n\n\n\nThe retirement of General Gro\ncant the chairmanship of Merchant Marine and\nFisheries and 2 desirable seat on the small but\ninfluential Committee on Rules. It has been Sup\nposed that the 1atter would go to the energetic and\nefficient Republican whip, James Watson, but\nMr. Watson has entered the race for the nomina\ntion for Governor of Indiana, and this upsets pre\nvious caicuiations. it is essential that members of\n+he Rules Committee should be faithful in thelr\nattendance at the cessions of the House, for the\nmeetings are called on short notice, and if Mr.\nwatson is ilkely to pe absent conducting his\nIndiana campaign from now until next spring this\npium is likely to fall to Representative Sherman,\nof New York, who is one of the most able as weil\nas popular members of the House.\n\nProbably the fate of the shipping bill, which the\nPresident will urge. in his message and which the\nadministration hopes to see enacted, will depend\non the selection of the chairman of Merchant\nMarine. With the committee evenly divided, the\nchairman cast the dec:ding vote which brought ths\nbill out of committee last year, and it is regarded\nas likely that every aspirant will have to stand\nan examination as to his loyaity to the subsidy\npolicy before he receives consideration.\n\n\ni\n\nT nds, formerly\nheld by Major Lacey, of Towa. Frank W. Mcondell\nof Wyoming, the ranking member, wants the hace,\nbut it is doubtfut if he can be appointed, Deczinc\nhe is regarded as antagonistic to the administra\ntion's public land policies. This might not prcve\nan insurmountable obetacle, but if the Speaker is\nobliged to go against the administration\u2019s views in\nhis Ways and DMieans selections he may not care\nto do =o in the less important Public Lands selec\ntion.\n\n\na\nportant chairmanship\nof the Committee on Agriculture, and Speaker\nCannon is seriously considering the entire reorgani\nzation of the committee. The present a\nare that Representative Beott, of Kensas, will ob\ntain the chairmanship, although v\ngh Representative\nHenry, of Connecticut, the ranking membe\nanxious for the place. x, 1s\nsvenor leaves va\nChamp Clark to Introduce a Bill at the\nFirst Opportunity.\n\nWashington, Nov. 30.\u2014At the first opportunity\nafter the meeting of Congress Representative\nChamp Clark, of Missouri, will introduce a bill re\npealing the law imposing a duty on paper used for\nprinting. Following is the text of the measure:\nFrom and after the approval of this act no im\nport tax duty shall be collected upon white print\npaper or white bock paper, or upon any of the\nmaterials and ingredients used in the manufacture\nor composition of the same.\nWashington, Nov. 80.\u2014Senator-elect Uwen, of\nOklahoma, who was caller at the White House\nto-day, sald he had been assured that Oklahoma\nwould receive the $5,000,000 due from the national\ngovernment, appropriated in leu of school lands in\nIndian Territory, next week. This money, he sald,\nwould be deposited in state banks without delay,\n+hus relieving the financial situation in Oklahoma.\n\ni\n\n\nSPEAKER'S BU ISY DAY.\nMANY COMMI 17% E PLUMS.\nEvery House Member Hunts Mr.\nCannon for Sw\u00bbecial Preferment.\nSPEAKER'S BUSY DAY.\nMANY COMMITTEE PLUMS.\nEvery House Member Hunts Mr.\nCannon for Swyecial Preferment.\n{From The Tribune Bureau 1\n\nha Re I TL\nAls