fted with a rare\nfund of common sense, =O +hat the Speaker would\nlike to place him where his talents may ve of valua\n10 fhe House. Last year the Speaker made Mr.\nOlcdtt a member of ihe District Committee, and as\nit usually causes hard feeling to taxe a man {rom\nthe foot of a ccmmittes and make him chairman, it\nis not believed that the member from the 15th Dis\ntrict wili be s0 honored, but the District chairman\nship might be given to Mr. Vreeland and the Ap\npropriations chairmanship to Mr. Olcott, glthough\nshe ranking member, Samuel W. Smith, of Michi\ngan, is the most likely candidate.\nThe retirement of General Grosvenor jeav\ncant the chairmanship of Merchant Marine and\nFisheries and 2 desirable seat on the small but\ninfluential Committee on Rules. It has been SuUp\nposed that the latter would E0 to the energetic and\nefficient Republican whip, James E. Watson, but\nMr. Watson has entered the race tor the nomina\ntion for Governor\nvious caicuiations.\nes vVa\nit is essential that members of\n+he Rules Commu\nattendance at the cessions of the House, for the\nmeetings are called on short notice, and if Mr.\nwatson is ilkely to pe absent conducting his\nIndiana campaign from now unt!! next spring this\npium is likely to fall to Representative Sherman,\nof New York, who is one of the most able as weil\nas popular members of the House.\nProbably the fa\nPresident will urge. in his message and which the\nadministration hopes to see enacted, will depend\non the selection of the chairman of Merchant\nMarine. With the committee evenly divided, the\nchairman cast\nthe dec:ding vote which brought the\na Liftaver, of New\nves wu dJesirablas vacancy on Appropria~\n{ll go to Mr. Vree-\nobtained u firmer grasp on conditions\nse than somes men do in\nof Indiana, and this upsets pre-\nittee should be faithful in their\nte of the shipping bill, which the\nbill out of committee last year, and it is regarded\nas likely that every aspirant will have to stand\nan examination as to his loyaity to the subsidy\npolicy before he receives consideration.\nA desirable vacancy, especially to Western mem\nbers, is the chairmansaip of Public Lands, formerly\nheld by Major Lacey, of Towa. Frank W. Mgndell,\nof Wyoming, the ranking member, wants the place,\nbut it is doubtfu if he can be appointed, because\nhe is regarded as antagonistic to the administra\ntion's public land policies. This might not prcve\nan insurmountable obstacle, but if the Speaker is\nobliged to go against the administration\u2019s views in\nhis Ways and DMieans selections he may not care\nto do =o in the less important Public Lands selec\ntion.\nThe retirement of James W. Wadsworth, of New\nYork, leaves vacant the important chairmanship\nof the Committee on Agriculture, and Speaker\nCannon is seriously considering the entire reorgani\nzation of the committee. The present indications\nare that Representative Beott, of Kensas, will ob\ntain the chairmanship, although Representative\nHenry, of Connecticut, the ranking member, is\nanxious for the place.\nWOULD REPEAL DUTY ON PAPER.\na E\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nAMARA A\ni\nWOULD REPEAL DUTY ON PAPER.\nGOVERNMENT CASH FOR OKLAHOMA.\nwAMAN SET FIRE TO HERSELF.\nPottstown, Penn. Nov. 8\u00a2.\u2014Despondent because\nof continued ili health and suffering from mental\naberration, Mrs. Charles Miller, the wife of\nprominent farmer of Fricks Locks, two miles east\nof here, poured a gallon of coal ofl over her body\nand lighted it to-day. She then ran to the barn\nwhere her husband was milking cows, and, seeing\nher afire, he seized a pai} of milk and threw the\ncontents over her. Neighbors rushed to his assist\nance and the flames were extinguished. The\nwoman, who will die, had made two previous ai\nNEW-YORK DAILY TRIBUNE, SUNDAY. DECEMBER 1. 1907.\nLY CELIA HARRINGTON, 303 Second Ave. Detroit, Mich., writes:\n\u201cWeakness has filled many months of my life with suffering.\nA\nISS\n\u201cThrough carelessness I caught a severe cold two years ago which settled in\ncatarrh and seriously interfered with the regular functions of the body and made me\nnervous and irritable. i\n\u201cI began taking Peruna and fou.d in it a faithful helper, as it enriched my blood\nand invigorated the whole system.\n\u201clI have no pains now, and am always well.\u201d\n\u201cT heartily recommend FPeruna as a reliable medicine.\u201d\n3\nMrs. A. E. Stouffer, Capioma, Kansas, writes:\n\u201cPeruna has given me health and strength;\nit is the best medicine that was ever mads {or\nwomen. My friends say they never saw such a\nchange in 2 woman. I talk to every ons about\nPeruna. I cannot say tco much for it.\u201d\nPe-ru-na in Tablet Form.\u2014For two years Dr.\nHartman and his assistants have incessantly\nlabored to create Peruna in tablet form, and\nthelr strenuous labors have just been crowned\nwith success. People who object to liquid medi\ncines can now secure Peruna Tablets, which\nrepresent ths medicinal ingredients of Peruna.\nEach tablet is equivalent to one average doses of\nPeruna.\nTT ORE CET amy oR 1\nNO HASTE ON CURRENCY\nNO HASTE ON CURRENCY\nLEADERS ARE CAUTIOUS.\nFinancial Legislation Must Wait\nUntil After Holiday Recess.\nLEADERS ARE CAUTIOUS.\nFinancial Legislation Must Wait\nUntil After Holidau Recess.\n(UR A448 AlVE ANEeA-2\nWashington, Nov 30.\u2014There will be no finan\ncial legisiation before Congress takes its holiday\nrecess, and the indications are that none will be\nenacted for some time thereafter, although it is\ngenerally expected that some measure of this\ncharacter will be passed before final adjourn\nment is taken. Tho leaders ars all here now,\nand thelr arrival has served to confirin the im\npression previously entertained that expedition\nwill not characterize tha course of either ths\nSenate or the House.\nSpeaker Cannon, Senator Aldrich and Chair\nman Fowler of the Banking and Currency Com\nmittee, have had no conference, but the views of\nthe Speaker and the chairman of the Senate\nFinance Committes appear to be in entire ac\ncord. Nelther favors hasty action by Congress,\ni\nIt is argued that the present financial crisis\nhas been weathered and has yielded te the\nmeasures of relief already adopted by the ad\nministration; that agitation of the question, such\nas would be inevitable were a flnancial measure\ncalled up for discussion in either house, would\nhave tendency to retard the recovery from the\nfinancial flurry, and that, finally, an effort to\nlegislate expeditiously would almost inevitably\nresult in the passgge of iid advised or ill con\nsidered measures. Under these circumstances, it\nis maintained that the best progress is that\nwhich will be made slowly.\n\n\n\u201cThe Senate will act with its usual care and\ndeliberation, and at the proper time will doubt\nless pass a carefully drawn and thoroughly con\nsidered measure,\u201d said a prominent member of\nthe Finance Committee to-day.\n\u201cThe Speaker, with his unfailing good sense,\nsees no occasion for hasty action, and, beyond\nthe possible strengthening of the Committee on\nBanking and Currency, will do nothing to hasten\nfinancial legislation in the House. The House\nwill doubtless weit until the Senate has acted,\u201d\neaid a prominent and influential member of the\nHouse.\n\n\nReports to the effect that the Speaker would\nappoint the Committee on Banking and Cur\nrency in advance of the other committees proved\nto be unfounded. The rumor that Somator\nAldrich was coming to Washington with a pre\npared measure which he would rush through\nthe Senate proved equally fallacious. The Sen\nator from Rhode Island has not even mentally\ndrafted a financial measure. Of course, he has\nwell defined ideas as to what legislation should\nbe enacted. He had those a year and more ago,\nbut saw no possibility of the adoption of such a\nmeasure as he deemed prudent, in view of the\ncomposition of the House committee, which\nwould have to deal with it. Consequently, he\nwas obliged to content himself with the mod\nerate and tentatively remedial enactment of the\nlast Congress.\nThe belief that some financial legislation of a\nremedial character will be enacted appears to\nbe general. Many members of both houses have\nmeasures which they are convinced will prove\nthe salvation of the finances of the country, and\nthe prospect of considerable more or less desul\ntory debate is excellent, but the leaders say\nthat ultimately something will be done, and\nthat when it is done it will be of a character\nfar more creditable to the party than any \u201chalf\nbaked\u201d legislation passed under the pressure of\na rapidly passing emergency.\n\nSenator Aldrich, chairman of the Committee\non Finance, was at the Capitol to-day, and\nspent most of the time in conference with Re\npublican leaders on the financial situation and\nlegisiation bearing on it. Senators Allison and\nHale took part in the discussion, but no con\n.lusions were made public.\ncECOND ANNUAL RECOUNT DECIDED.\nChief Justice Gummere of the Supreme Court in\nNew Jersey yesterday passed on the ballots that\nhad been referred to him in the Wright-Masker\naldermanic recount in ahe 1st Ward of Newark,\nand decided that Joseph A. Wright, the Democrat,\nhad been elected over William U. Masker, the Re\npublican, by 2 majority of 16. When Wright was\nelected for the term which he is at present serving\nhe had a majority of 2 over Masker on the face of\nha poturns. Masker obtained recount, but lost.\nISS HARRINGTON GF DETROIT\nqn i 7 SAYS:\n\u00abI Caught\niil a Severe\nWl Settled in\nCatarrh.\nI Began\nTaking\nPe-ru-na\nHelper.\nI Heartily\nRecommend\n\n8\nPe-ru-na.\u201d\u2019\nMISS CELIA HARRINGTON.\nCELIA HARRINGTON, 303 Second Ave. Detroit, Mich., writes:\nWeakness has filled many months of my life with suffering.\nThrough carelessness I caught a severe cold two years ago which settled in\nand seriously interfered with the regular functions of the body and made mse\nand irritable.\nvega