d\nit a Faithful\nHelper.\nI Heartily\nRecommend\nMISS CELIA HARRINGTON.\nHealth and Strenath Restored.\nAsc Your Druggist for Free Peruna Almanac for 16o8.\nIevyam The Tribune Bureau.)\nSUNDAY, DECEMBER 1. 1907.\nFor Years an Invalid.\nMrs. Charles Gros Louis, Indian Lorette, Que\nbec, Canada, writes:\n\ni\n\n\u201cFor vears 1 suffered from a disease that the\ndoctors did not understand.\n\n\ni\n\n\u201cOne day I read in the paper about your ex\ncellent remedy, Peruna. 1 procured a bottle of\nit and took it according to directions. It was\nnot long until I observed a change for the bet\nter.\ni\n\n\n\n\n\u201cI ean say that Peruna has cured me. I could\nnot take any nourishment except milk.\n\u201cI will at all times say a gcod word for Pe\nruna. [I hold it in the highest esteem.\u201d\n\nCatarrh of Head and Throat.\nMrs. William H. Hinchliffe, 20 Myrtle St,\nBeverly, Mass, writes that Peruna has done her\na great deal of good for catarrh of head and\nthroat.\n\n\nbe FD atta i RE ood eS ae eR\nBRYAN MUM GN HEARST\nAnything Like a Hypothetical Ques\nlion FE rcites His Apprehension,\nWilliam J. Pryan will not discuss parties or per\nsoralities\u2014when they are troublesome. Nor will\nhe answer hypothetical questions.\n\u201cWhat are you golng to do with Willlam R.\nHearst and his Independence League?\u2019 was the\nquestion asked Mr. Bryan last evening at the\nHeffman House.\ni\n\n\u201c1 cannot discuss personailties or parties,\u201d said\nMr. Bryan quickly and good naturedly. \u201cIn all of\nmy discussions I strive to stick to principles, rather\nthan personalities.\u2019\n\n\u201cBut Mr. Hearst stands for certain political\nprinciples; he has a national organization, with\nthe balance of power in three or four states. You\nwill have to deal with him sconer or later; why\nnot \u00a2iscuss him now?\u201d\nMr. Bryan waved away the interrogation as he\nwould a gadfly. On a recent visit here Mr. Bryan\nfound time to call on Mr. Hearst at his home in\nLexington avenue. He was discovered there by\nWilliam Astor Chanler, whe is prosecuting Mr.\nHearst for alleged libel. Not until Mr. Chanler\u2019s\naffidavit was made public was it generally known\nthat Mr. Bryan had recently met Mr. Hearst. Mr.\nBryan refused to say what he had talked about.\n\nTre hypothetical question was prompted by \u2018the\nassumption that {industrial stagnation would have\nno terrors for Mr. Bryan as President, once he\nwas fairly begun in a crusade on predatory wealth.\nThis was the question:\n\n\u201cIf an Executive finds that the carrying out of a\ncertain policy brings about an industrial and\nfinancial depression, throwing thousands of labor\ning men out of work and distressing them, has ha\nany right to continue the poilcy 7\"\n\u2018*Phat\u2019s a hyvothetical question,\u2019 he said. ba\nvoy have studie?! the philosophy of hypothetical\nquestions you must Know that they ar< not falr un\nless all the eiements of a situation &re compre\nhended. Do you think your question includes all\n4\nthe elements?\u2019\n\u201cWell, I don't,\u201d =aid Mr. Bryan, with an expan\nsive smile.\n\u201cIf you're elected President won't you be up\nagainst that very question?\u2019 was asked.\n\u201c1 cannot answer hypothetical questions,\u201d said\nAr. Bryan. \u2018Some years ago a newspaper opposed\nto me framed a hypothetical question in such a\nmanner that when it was submitted to a celebrated\nalienist the alienist decided that 1 was a lunatic.\nMy reasons for objecting to hypothetical questions\n\nshould be obvious.\u201d\nA representative of\nnumber of questions, one of whi\n\n\nMr. Bryan, who said:\n\u00abphe World\u2019 has been both malicious and un\nscrupulous in lying about me. This week it took\nme to task for voting for Weaver. It utterly ig\nd the fact that we were instructed to vote for\nat that course would better\n\u201cThe World\u201d then asked a\n\u2018hh seemed to nettle\nnore\nWeaver .n the belief th\nassist Cleveland. It accuses me of being the cause\nof the shrinkuge in the Democratic vote. In the\ntwo campaigns in which I was opposed by \u2018The\nWorld\u00ae I recelved more votes by about one and a\nquarter millions than were cast for Judge Parker,\nwhose nomination was fathered by \u2018The World\"\nand who was valiantly supported by \u201cThe Werld.\u201d\nMr. Bryan left last evening in company with his\ndaughters, Mrs. Leavitt and Miss Grace Bryan, for\nTorrington, Conn. This morning he will go from\nTorrington by special train to Derby, where he will\nassist in the dedication of an Elks\u2019 Hall. This af\nternoon he is scheduled to speak to the Young\nMen's Christian Association in Brooklyn, and to\nnight he will lecture in the Westminster Presby\nterian Church.\nINSISTS OHIO IS FOR TAFT.\nA. I. Vorys Says Secretary's Friends Will\nwelcome Test with Foraker.\nColumbus, Ohto, Nov. 50.--A. I. Vorys, campaign\nmanager for Secretary Tatt, said to-day regarding\nSenator Foraker's Presidential candidacy:\n\u201cOhio Republicans have determined their choice,\nand this preference is for Secretary Taft. It is\nshown by the attitude of tha press of the state,\nby the public and by private expressions of state\nofficials, Congressmen, state legislators and hun\ndreds of other active party men, and by the In\ndorsement of Taft by the state committee, bY\nnumerous county committees and by other organi\nzations of Ohio Republicans. The friends of Sec\nretary Taft, as 1 have repeatedly said, will wei\ncome an early opportunity to submit the question\ndiretly to Ohio Republicans or their representatives\nin state convention.\u201d\n\nSENATOR COHALAN'\u2019S SUIT GOES ON.\nThe trial of the sult to recover 300,000 damages\nfrom \u2018The World\" by State Senator John P. Coha\nlan was continued in the Supreme Court yesterday\nbefore Justice Brady and a jury. Cohalan\u2019s suit\nis based on an article commenting on the action of\nhimself and other Senators in voting against the\nremoval of Otto Kelsey as State Superintendent of\nInsurance.\nDETROIT\nSAYS:\nJIG\n2\nnm oc\nak\nJohn Daniel Sonst Sons\nARE OFFERING A LARGE AND EXCLUSIVE COLLECTION OF SOLIC GOLD,\nGOLD FILLED AND ORIENTAL\nJEWELRY\nFOR CHRISTMAS GIFTS\nWATCHES, GOLD, GOLD FILLED, SILVER, GUN METAL AND ENAMELLED,\nFOR MEM, WOMEN AND CHILDREN, AT EXCEPTIONALLY LOW PRICES.\nBROOCHES, SCARF PINS AND RINGS,\nWITH DIAMONDS, PEARLS AND OTHER\nSEMI-PRECIOUS STONES......... ae ue aes 1.50 to 175.00\nibn UR SN 50 to 45.00\nFi\nA fLeTeI SOLID GOLD, OLD FINED 95 to 75.00\nVEIL AND COLLAR PINS, NEAT DESIGNS............... 253 to 7.95\nCOMBS, ARTISTIC DESIGNS. co... ooiiearuannnnns 50 ic 14.50\nSILVER PLATED PURSES; $1.75 VALUE, FOR.......... 95\nOPERA GLASSES, PEARL OR LEATHER...... Bas. 2.25 to 42.50\nFANS, OF FEATHERS, LACE OR SPANGLED............ 530 to 14.00\nLeather Goods, Purses, &c.\nLEATHER TRAVELLING BAGS.....cccuvueeecnnnnaennnnnn 5.00 to 15.00\nLEATHER SUIT BASES. .....coniriirrrrnrusnsstrnanssvasas 4.935 to 17.50\nLEATHER COVERED FLASKS .......ccoouoeuueeunnannnnn. B55 to 5.50\nMEDICINE CASES. ini ivsdisinnsassnase 63 to 6.00\nLEATHER COLLAR BAGS AND BOXES. ..........cccnu... 50 to 4.35\nEEATHER CURR CASES... cove ccsisinanstinnanss 95 to 3.25\nLEATHER HANDKERCHIEF AND\nGLOVE BOXES i cccivientas ars 95, 1.10, 1.35\nLEATHER SEWING BOXES.........cco.concecientancncane 25 to 8.50\nRICH GOLD AND LEATHER PHOTO\nBRANES. mS 25 to 5.00\nSTERLING SILVER FRAMES....... a ea ae 95 to 14.75\n1000 DIARIEBL.. coer srvascansca sen IE RE I 25 to 3.50\nLEAVHER MANDEBAGS. 2. un cssie sas cstsrassnecsss 250 to 15.50\nPOCKET BOOKS, CARD CASES,\nBILL ROLLS AND WALLETS. ......ccercrsnrmacssnscnnes 50 te 5.00\nMESH BAGS AND PURSES,\nGILT AND GERMAN SILVER... .0uoaeeneenneenaenannnnn 1.93 io 13.25\nGUN METAL BAGS.............. RII Wd OIE CT 3.95 to 12.00\nSTERLING SIEVER BAGS. Mu coeererrrrressarsnnnecas 28.00 a2 43.00\nBEAT BUCIKEES. oer sirname te Tartana 50 to 10.00\non RE Se AR IE SCE SE I 350 to 7.50\ns ss na\nIn the Basement\nWE HAVE THIS YEAR DEVOTED AN ENLARGED SECTION TO THE EX\nCLUSIVE SALE OF BEAUTIFUL\nCHRISTMAS CARDS. CAROLS, CALENDARS, HYMNS,\nBOOKLETS AND MOTTOES.\nA MILLION TO SELECT FROM.\nTHE G00D OLD HOME TRADITIONS OF CHRISTMAS HAVE BEEN CHER\nISHED BY THIS ESTABLISHMENT SINCE ITS ORGANIZATION 50 YEARS\nAGO.\nTHIS SECTION IS BRILLIANTLY ILLUMINATED, WELL VENTILATED,\nCOVERING AN AREA CF 15,000 SQUARE FEET AND VERY ACCESSIBLE.\nSUNDAY SCHOOLS AND FAIRS SUPPLIED.\n1\nMAIL AND TELEPHONE ORDERS FILLED AT ONCE.\nBroadway, 8th and 9th Sts.\nBroadway, 8th and 9th Sts.\nDEPEW AFRAID TO SWIM.\nre\nCauses of Financial Trouble Too\nDeep for Him.\n[From The Tribune Bureau.)\nWashington, Nov. .\u2014Senator Depew called at\nthe White House to-day and discussed the financial\nsituation at length, but when asked to express\nhimself on the causes of the present flurry in\nmoney and the Presidential succession he fled.\n\u201cWhen you ask me to go into the causes of\nthe financial troubles.\u201d he said, \u201cyou Invite me\ninto a sea so broad, so deep and so stormy that\nI do not think I'll try to swim.\u201d\n\u201cHow about the Presidency?\u201d he was asked.\n\u201cOh. that's another sea,\u201d he replied.\ntore fleeing from the tempestuous waters of\nthe two oceans, the Senator sald he favored the\ncurrency plans advocated by the New York bankers\nand the New York Chamber of Commerce, \u201cwhich\nare much alike, though slightly different in form.\u201d\nhe sald.\n\u201cWe'll have currency legislation this session)\u2019\nhe continued, \u201cbut we'll not get it in a minut\nAfter living under financial laws for fifty years, we\ncan't change them In fifty days. Whatever we do\nshould be accomplished only after the most care\nful consideration, for it's a very serious matter\nindeed. It would be better to have no new cur\nrency legielation at all than to put through some\nthing hasty and ill considered. I am in favor of\nan asset currency that can be expanded fn emer\ngencles like the present. Germany. France and\nCanada all have schemes of this sort which seem\nto work well. Canada may increase her currency\nin emergencies to the extent of about $60,000,000, if\nI am not mistaken in the figures. and never vet\nhas she been obliged to issue to the limit. The\nemergency currency should be heavily taxed. If\nit is, it will be used when it is badly needed, and\nwill be retired automatically as soon as the need\nfor it has passed.\u201d\nAMERICANS WON'T WORK, SAYS SMOOT\nHopes Financial Troubles Will Teach Them\na Lesson.\n[From The Tribune Bureau.\nFRAC Aes\nWashington, Nov. 30.\u2014 The Americans wont\nwork any more. They are so busy speculating and\ntrying to live off of each other that they have\nabandoned labor, and the foreigner collects the\n\nwages and sends the money abroad.\u201d\nThis is the arrzignment of the nation delivered\nby Senator Reed Smoot, of Utah, at the White\nHouse to-day. Senator Smoot laid much of the\nblame for the present financial stringency upon the\nshoulders of his work-no-more countrymen, and\nsaid he hoped the money troubles would teach\nthem a lesson.\n\n\u201cOut in my state and in the surrounding states\nyou cannot find an American laborer.\u201d sald Mr.\nSmoot. \u201cAll the work is performed by foreigners,\nmostly Greeks at present, and th\u00e9 moment they get\ntheir pay they ship every cent of it that they can\nspare from their bare living expenses to their\nhomes in 1i1hs old country. That means more\nGreeks. I do not think that the postal bank, as\nsuggested by Postmaster-General Meyer. or any\nother scheme of government guarantee would keep\nthat money from going across the ocean. If the\nforeigner is paid more money than he actually\nneeds to ive on he will send it home. Perhaps the\nfinancial! panic will teach us 2 lesson, and some\ntime in the future the Americans will go back to\nwork. In the last few years our people have been\ntoo busy gambling and speculating to do any real\nwork. They have been too much engaged in rob\nbing each other.\u201d\n\nSenator Smoot said he advocated a currency law\nwhich would allow the expansion of the volume\nof money in emergencies, and believed that such a\nlaw would be passed by the incoming Congress.\n\u00abThis e: iergency currency should be heavily taxed,\nat least 7 per cent.\u201d he added. \u201cso that it would\nvanish as soon as the panic was over.\u201d Tx\nFOR DEMOCRATIC CLUB GOVERNORS.\nAt the annual meeting of the governors of the\nNational Democratic Club to-morrow night the\ntoliowing will be added to the board of governors,\ntheir terms to expire in December, 1910: Warren\nWwW. Foster, Herman A. Mets, Herman Ridder,\nSamuel Untermysr, Richard Croker. In, John HL\n27\n\nJEWELRY\nPhone.2 380. Co Iumbus\nTourists find a reliable friend in the Taxa\nmeter.\nFor prompt service at a moderats chargs,\nplainly indicated, phone us from your room.\nHANSOM OR COUPE\nFist }-2mila. a. 30 cts.\nEach 1-4 mile thereafter............ 10 cts.\nEach 6 minutes waiting. 10 cts.\nFor sending cab to address, per mile\nOF feactitmy. .....canenccacaacns 20 cts.\nSent on phone order day or night.\nMay be hailed and engaged on the street\nwhen the flag is up.\nTariffs boy: information on request.\n\u2018NEW YORK TRANSPORTATION CO.\nEighth Avenue at Forty-Ninth Street.\nLincoln Trust Company\nMadison Square\nand\nBroadway Lispenard St.\nBroadway and 72d Street\nThe present condition of the\nmoney market enables this\ncompany to offer exceptionally\nfavorable interest rates on\nmoney awaiting investment\nor otherwise temporarily idle.\nCampbell, Henry Steinert, John J. Quinlan, John\nF. Mcintyre, George Ehret, jr, and Eugene IL.\nBushe. The terms of John R. Dunlap, Thomas L.\nFeitner and James Shevlin expire in December,\n158. The annval report of John H. Campbell, the\ntreasurer, shows the total receipts for the year to\nhave been 391.698 08, with disbursements of $96,759 50,\nreducing the balance in the treasury from 313.618 41\nto 38.547 41.\nSUICIDE IN HOSPITAL\nWealthy Patient Uses Gun in\nSwedish Institution.\nThomas Armstrong. seventy-one vears eld. a\nmanufacturer of leather findings living at Neo.\n$20 Lexington avenue, Brooklyn, shot and killed\nhimself yesterday afternoon while confined In\none of the wards of the Swedish Hospital,\nBrooklyn. His death is being investigated by\nthe coroners\u2019 office and by the police.\nArmstrong was found lying at Fraankiln and\nLexington avenues yesterday morning and taken\nto the hospital in an ambulance, where it was\nsaid that he was suffering with la grippe. When\nhis clothing was searched a fully loaded .38cali\nbre revolver was found. A. When an attempt was\nmade to take the revolver Armsircng objected so\nstrenuously he was allowed to retain the weapon\nand keep it under his pillow. One of the nurses\nwent in to see him about 3 o'clock and found\nhim all right. When she returned in fifteen\nminutes she found him dead. He had held the\nrevolver under the bedclothes so as to muffle the\nsound and shot himself in the right side.\n\n5\nBasiite.\nTo. AF","height":"35088","width":"25384"}}
